  footnotes: []
english:
  title: In Response to Taekji
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    We lament that worldly affairs come too late to grasp,
    yet making friends arrives too soon to trust.
    I am but twenty-four years old,
    and all things clash against my youthful hopes.

    I dread each passing moment in my dreams,
    that fleeting years will steal me into age.
    The friends who knew my heart throughout my life
    are scattered like dust upon the road.

    Of late, I marvel at how desolate it grows—
    the gate and courtyard swept as if abandoned.
    What use to ponder ancient times and present?
    Gain and loss alike prove trivial.

    The worthy hide themselves in mountain woods,
    while lesser men don the brocade and silk.
    Alas, how pitiful the stalwart soul
    that withers like reeds left by the marsh.

    Fortune and misfortune twist together—
    I would question Heaven itself.
    Yet Heaven and Earth cannot endure forever,
    so how can mortal life be guaranteed?

    The flatterer's moment burns but briefly bright,
    like sudden rain pooling in the road.
    How can we treat the scholar lightly?
    His tattered robe conceals rare treasure.

    His name shall not fade through thousand autumns;
    the purple robes he never coveted.
    This poem stirs such sorrow in my breast,
    it leaves my troubled heart disturbed.

    Even the oriole seems to join my sighs,
    crying thrice before it flies beyond the eaves.
  footnotes:
    - Taekji (擇之) was likely a friend or contemporary of the poet; this poem is written in response to his work
    - The reference to being twenty-four suggests this was written in Park Eun's youth, a time of reflection on life's uncertainties
    - The imagery of scattered friends and desolate gates reflects the poet's sense of alienation and the transience of human connection
    - The final image of the oriole echoes traditional Chinese and Korean poetic convention, where birds often serve as witnesses to human emotion
